{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489501","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489501"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:19:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:19:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"674"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"674","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/674"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.34,0.33,0.08,0.14,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"674"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"26183"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"674","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/674"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"674"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"13425"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"393"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2495"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2521"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3854"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20505"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42127"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"26183","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/26183"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old man presents with a pigmented lesion over his right scapula. He is otherwise in good health and apart from the skin lesion, there are no other abnormal physical findings. The lesion is excised with a 2 mm margin of normal tissue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe histology reports that the lesion is a malignant melanoma and is 0.7 mm in Breslow thickness. It appears to have been completely removed, with normal tissue found at all margins of the tumour. The patient is concerned to know if he requires any further treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate advice?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Regular observation alone","Further excision (1 cm margin)","Further excision (2 cm margin)","Further excision (1 cm margin) and sentinel node biopsy","Further excision (2 cm margin) and sentinel node biopsy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EMelanomas of all types have a high malignant potential and in order to minimise this wide excisional margins are used. The key to guiding this the thickness of the lesion, using the Breslow thickness rules. Based on this, the margins needed are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMelanoma in-situ: 5-10mm margin\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThickness \u0026lt;1mm = 1cm margin\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThickness 1-4mm = 1-2cm margin, increasing as thickness increases and with clinical decision\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThickness \u0026gt;4mm = 2cm margin\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other consideration is a sentinel lymph node biopsy, as the this will be the first site malignant cells will lodge following metastasis. SLN biopsy is recommended with thickness \u0026gt;0.8mm and should be done by those with experience. It is important to note that if draining nodes are palpable = clinically detected, then biopsy is not needed as this is sufficient indication for complete removal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStaging of melanoma takes into account the breslow thickness and sentinel node biopsy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStage 0 - melanoma in situ\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStage 1 - breslow thickness up to 1mm and only confined to skin. Stage 1b if melanoma is ulcerated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStage 2 - breslow thickness 1-4mm and confined to skin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStage 3 - melanoma of any thickness + spread to sentinel lymph node or nearby skin\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStage 4 - spread to internal organ or lymph node not in sentinel chain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this patient the thickness of the melanoma is 0.7 mm and a \u003Cstrong\u003Efurther excision to produce a 1 cm margin\u003C/strong\u003E is all that is required. With this thickness (\u0026lt;0.75 mm) the risk of metastatic spread is very low (\u0026lt;5%) and a SLN biopsy is not necessary.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The Breslow thickness is used to determine the need for further excision and the need for a sentinel lymph node biopsy."],"references":["Sladden MJ, Nieweg OE, Howle J, Coventry BJ, Thompson JF. Updated evidence-based clinical practice guidelines for the diagnosis and management of melanoma: definitive excision margins for primary cutaneous melanoma.\u00a0MJA; 2018: 208(3).","Thompson JF, Scolyer RA, Kefford RF. Melanoma a management guide for GPs. Australian Family Physician. 2012; 41(7): 470-73."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"13425"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"674"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"13425","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/13425"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2022-08-01T14:37:26+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-28T22:08:07+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"674"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"26183"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"